data.content:
Yes! For simple inline data, `[DataRow]` is cleaner. For type safety with `DynamicData`, use tuples:

**Option 1 — `[DataRow]` (simplest for literals):**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

**Option 2 — Tuples with `DynamicData` (type-safe, better for complex/computed data):**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<object[]> TestData =>
    new (string input, bool expected)[]
    {
        ("valid@email.com", true),
        ("invalid", false),
        ("", false),
    }.Select(t => new object[] { t.input, t.expected });
```

**Recommendation:** Use `[DataRow]` here — your cases are all compile-time constants, so there's no need for `DynamicData`. Reserve `DynamicData` for when test data is computed, shared across tests, or too complex for attributes.
